The relationship between early phonological and lexical development

Summer School of Linguistics, Krom, Czech Republic

Mits Ota (University of Edinburgh)

This is a website for my lectures on early phonological and lexical development given at the Summer School of Linguistics on 9-12 August 2019. Scroll down to access lecture slides and links to references mentioned in the lectures. If you have any questions, please email me at mits@ling.ed.ac.uk.

Background readings

The following articles provide some general background for the main issues I will be discussing in the lecture.

  • Stoel-Gammon, C. (2011). Relationships between lexical and phonological development in young children. Journal of Child Language, 38, 1-34.
  • Swingley, D. (2009). Contributions of word learning to language development. Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society B, 364.
  • Vihman, M. M. (2017). Learning words and learning sounds: Advances in language development. British Journal of Psychology, 108, 1-27.

Slides

  • Lecture 1: Can sound categories be learned without words?
  • Lecture 2: How do phonological representations of words develop?
  • Lecture 3: How do lexical factors affect phonological development?
  • Lecture 4: How does phonology affect word learning?

Useful online resources

  • CHILDES: Corpus data of early langauge production.
  • MetaLabs early language data: Meta analyses of effects in early language development
  • Phonotactic probability and neighborhood density calculator: Include child corpus data for American English.
  • Wordbank: An open database of childrens vocabulary development.
